{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"63ddea97-b51b-47d7-9c24-1e5a0dbac522","content":"The current working directory is empty, so there's no project-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance based on .NET and macOS knowledge:\n\n---\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS writes to `/cores` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app. macOS will write a Mach-O core file (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n4. **If `/cores` is empty**, check that:\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking core dumps for your binary.\n   - The disk has sufficient space.\n   - The app isn't codesigned with the `com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory` restriction. You may need to re-sign or use `codesign --remove-signature`.\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **Install SOS/dotnet-dump** for managed analysis (if applicable):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`. The macOS kernel's built-in core dump mechanism (`/cores/core.*`) is the primary alternative.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7d1db9d9-b037-4a4b-ab04-d0d12c3b793e","outputTokens":385,"requestId":"2C44:97105:13FF82C:16CBD5A:69F94DCA"},"id":"c90ee636-a384-42d9-bf11-01b1d37f8740","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:54:27.779Z","parentId":"ed20d6c2-0592-4726-8fc3-435c4018ffd2"}
